Overview

Project Overview: RFM-Based Customer Segmentation with KMeans Clustering

This project applies unsupervised machine learning techniquesspecifically KMeans clusteringto segment customers based on their Recency, Frequency, and Monetary (RFM) behavior in an e-commerce context. The goal is to discover meaningful customer groups to support targeted marketing strategies and operational decision-making.

Objective

To identify distinct customer segments by analyzing their purchasing behavior and categorize them into clusters using KMeans. Each segment is interpreted from a business perspective to propose actionable strategies for retention, loyalty, or reactivation.

Dataset and Preprocessing

The dataset contains RFM metrics per customer:

  • Recency: Days since last purchase
  • Frequency: Number of purchases
  • Monetary: Total spending

To prepare the data:

  • Outliers were handled using bi-weight transformation.
  • MinMax scaling was applied to normalize the RFM values between 0 and 1.
  • KMeans was run with two different configurations:
    • K=3 clusters (rfmdata_bw_S_3C.csv)
    • K=4 clusters (rfmdata_bw_S_4C.csv)
  • Cluster assignments were merged back to the original unscaled data to compute real RFM averages per segment.

Methodology

  1. KMeans Clustering: Unsupervised grouping of customers based on similarity in RFM behavior.
  2. Evaluation of Cluster Centers: Average values per cluster for Recency, Frequency, and Monetary were analyzed using denormalized data to improve interpretability.
  3. Cluster Profiling:
    • Size of each cluster (number of customers)
    • RFM characteristics
    • Business interpretation of each group

Use Cases and Business Value

  • Loyalty Programs: Identify and reward high-frequency and high-monetary customers.
  • Churn Risk Management: Detect recent inactivity to trigger win-back campaigns.
  • Resource Allocation: Prioritize efforts on valuable or at-risk segments.

This segmentation enables personalized marketing, better budget allocation, and improved customer lifetime value (CLV) management.

Tools Used

  • Python (Pandas, Scikit-learn, Matplotlib)
  • KMeans Clustering
  • MinMaxScaler
  • Custom profiling and denormalization logic

Next Steps

  • Evaluate more granular segmentations (e.g., K=5, K=6)
  • Track customer transitions between clusters over time
  • Integrate with campaign performance data for ROI analysis

2.2. RFM Data creation and RFM Data Description

In[4]:
# 1. Clean the dataset
rfm_source_data = ordata.copy()
rfm_source_data = rfm_source_data.dropna(subset=["CustomerID"])
rfm_source_data = rfm_source_data[(rfm_source_data["Quantity"] > 0) & (rfm_source_data["UnitPrice"] > 0)]
rfm_source_data["InvoiceDate"] = pd.to_datetime(rfm_source_data["InvoiceDate"])

# 2. Define the reference date (day after last invoice)
reference_date = rfm_source_data["InvoiceDate"].max() + pd.Timedelta(days=1)

# 3. Compute RFM features
rfmdata = rfm_source_data.groupby("CustomerID").agg({
    "InvoiceDate": lambda x: (reference_date - x.max()).days,  # Recency
    "InvoiceNo": "nunique",                                     # Frequency
    "Quantity": lambda x: np.sum(x * rfm_source_data.loc[x.index, "UnitPrice"])  # Monetary
}).reset_index()

# 4. Rename columns
rfmdata.columns = ["CustomerID", "Recency", "Frequency", "Monetary"]

3.2. Basic Statistical Information

This section provides a detailed statistical overview of both the raw transactional dataset and the aggregated RFM dataset. The goal is to understand the distribution, scale, and behavior of key variables before moving on to normalization and clustering.

Understanding the underlying statistics is essential in clustering tasks because most clustering algorithms particularly distance-based methods like K-Means are sensitive to the scale and variability of the input features. Anomalous values or skewed distributions can distort distances between points and lead to suboptimal or misleading clusters.

The analysis begins with descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, percentiles, etc.) to summarize key characteristics of the data, followed by a structured outlier analysis to detect and mitigate the effect of extreme values that could bias clustering outcomes.

The statistical examination is performed at two levels:

  • Raw Dataset Level: Analyzing individual transaction records such as Quantity and UnitPrice.
  • RFM Dataset Level: Analyzing customer-level aggregated features Recency, Frequency, and Monetary derived from the raw dataset.

By exploring both datasets, we ensure a comprehensive understanding of the data before transformation and modeling. The insights gathered here will directly inform decisions in the next phases, including feature scaling, cluster selection, and model evaluation.

EXPLANATION OF STANDARD DEVIATION How to Interpret if Standard Deviation is High or Low

When describing variability in a dataset, the standard deviation () is evaluated in relation to the mean ().
A general rule of thumb is to compare the ratio / (called the coefficient of variation, CV).

  • Low variability:
    If / < 0.2 (less than 20%), the spread is considered small compared to the mean.
    Data points are clustered close to the average.

  • Moderate variability:
    If 0.2 / 0.5, the spread is moderate.
    Data points are fairly dispersed, but the mean still represents the dataset reasonably well.

  • High variability:
    If / > 0.5 (greater than 50%), the spread is large relative to the mean.
    Data is widely spread, and extreme values (outliers) are more likely.

Example (Raw Dataset Quantity)

  • Mean () 9.55
  • Std () 218.08
  • Ratio / = 218.08 / 9.55 22.8

Since this ratio is >> 0.5, the standard deviation is considered extremely high, confirming that outliers (very large or negative quantities) are distorting the distribution. Conclusion Calling a standard deviation high is not about the absolute value, but about its size relative to the mean. The coefficient of variation provides a consistent, general rule for interpretation across different variables and datasets.

3.2.2. Outlier Analysis

Detecting outliers before applying clustering algorithms is a critical step in ensuring high-quality, interpretable customer segmentationnot only in the raw transaction-level data but also in the engineered RFM dataset.

Clustering algorithmsespecially centroid-based ones like K-Meansare highly sensitive to extreme values. Outliers can:

  • Distort cluster centroids, shifting them away from the true center of dense customer groups.
  • Lead to artificial clusters that dont represent real customer behavior.
  • Reduce the interpretability and actionability of the final segments.
  • Inflate distance-based metrics, such as inertia and silhouette score, causing misleading performance evaluation.

In the case of the Raw dataset, outliers in variables like Quantity, UnitPrice, and CustomerID may indicate returns, refunds, or data entry errors (e.g., negative or extreme values). These anomalies can propagate into RFM features if left unaddressed.

In the RFM dataset, even after aggregation, extreme values in Recency, Frequency, or Monetary may still existeither due to high-spending customers or unusually inactive ones. These can skew distance metrics or dominate the clustering process unless properly handled.

*Outlier Detection Methods*

Two robust statistical techniques will be applied to both datasets:

Z-score Method:

  • Measures how many standard deviations a point is from the mean.
  • A common threshold is Z-score 3 or -3.
  • Best for symmetric, approximately normal distributions.

IQR Method (Interquartile Range):

  • Defines outliers as points lying outside [Q1 - 1.5IQR, Q3 + 1.5IQR].
  • Robust to skewed distributions and ideal for transactional or monetary data.

Each dataset (Raw and RFM) will be analyzed independently using both methods, and we will document:

  • The number and percentage of outliers per variable.
  • The impact of each method.
  • A brief strategy for handling them (e.g., removal, capping, or transformation).

This step ensures that subsequent clustering results reflect true customer behaviors, enabling more reliable and effective segmentation strategies.

3.2.2.1.1. Initial Outlier Detection
In[11]:
# Function to detect outliers for all numeric features in a DataFrame
def detect_outliers_summary(df, numeric_columns, z_threshold=3):
    summary = {}
    unique_outliers = set()

    for col in numeric_columns:
        # Z-score method
        z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df[col]))
        z_outliers = df.index[z_scores > z_threshold]
        z_outlier_count = len(z_outliers)

        # IQR method
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        iqr_outliers = df.index[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)]
        iqr_outlier_count = len(iqr_outliers)

        summary[col] = {
            "z_outliers_count": z_outlier_count,
            "iqr_outliers_count": iqr_outlier_count,
        }

        unique_outliers.update(z_outliers)
        unique_outliers.update(iqr_outliers)

    summary['unique_outliers_count'] = len(unique_outliers)

    return summary

To visually explore these outliers we use boxplots and variable distribution graphs.
___Boxplots___ are useful for visually identifying outliers by displaying the minimum, first quartile (Q1), median (Q2), third quartile (Q3), and maximum values, with outliers appearing as individual points beyond the whiskers. They help detect skewness, variability, and extreme values in a dataset, making it easier to decide on outlier treatment strategies. ___Distribution plots___ (histograms with KDE) provide a deeper insight into the overall shape of the data, showing whether the distribution is normal, skewed, or multimodal. Combining boxplots and distribution graphs allows for a comprehensive exploration of data anomalies, ensuring better preprocessing decisions before applying machine learning models.

  • Boxplot Observations:

    • Clear presence of extreme outliers, including both high positive and negative values.
    • Negative quantities suggest product returns or data entry errors.
    • The core distribution (IQR) is compressed near zero, indicating that most transactions involve small quantities.

  • Histogram Observations:

    • Most values are concentrated around small positive quantities.
    • A long tail in both directions (especially negative) confirms a heavily skewed distribution.
    • The distribution is non-normal and has heavy tails, justifying the large number of IQR-detected outliers.

UnitPrice

  • Boxplot Observations:

    • Several high-value outliers exist, as well as negative prices, which are likely data errors or refunds recorded incorrectly.
    • The interquartile range is narrow, meaning most unit prices are small (likely below 5).

  • Histogram Observations:

    • A sharp spike at low values confirms the presence of low-cost retail items.
    • A long positive tail shows rare but extreme prices, potentially luxury items or price input mistakes.
    • Negative prices must be investigated or removed before analysis.

Summary and Recommendations

  • Both features exhibit severe outliers that can negatively impact clustering results, especially in distance-based methods like K-Means.
  • Negative values in both Quantity and UnitPrice are illogical in a typical sales context and must be addressed.
  • Suggested actions before modeling:
    • Remove or correct negative values.
    • Use IQR-based filtering or quantile clipping to treat extreme outliers.
    • Optionally, consider log-transforming skewed variables (after removing negatives) for better scaling in clustering.
3.2.2.1.2. Outlier Handling Methods (for Clustering)

To address the extreme values identified in the Quantity and UnitPrice variables, we apply two widely used outlier treatment techniques. These will result in two alternative versions of the dataset, which will later be used to train and compare clustering models:

  • Winsorization (dataset: ordata_w)
  • IQR Method Removal (dataset: ordata_r)

This approach allows us to evaluate the impact of each strategy on the clustering results, particularly on cluster cohesion and separation.

Truncation-Winsorization on *ordata_w*. Winsorization caps extreme values to reduce the influence of outliers without removing any records.

Implementation Steps:

  • For each numeric variable, values below the 1st percentile and above the 99th percentile are capped to those limits.
  • Negative values for Quantity and UnitPrice, which are logically invalid, are removed after capping.

Pros: Retains all observations, preserving the full customer base and reduces the distortion caused by extreme values in distance-based clustering (e.g., K-Means).
Cons: May still introduce artificial similarity across capped values and Residual skewness may persist, affecting scaling and cluster shapes.

IQR Method Removal on *ordata_r*. The IQR method filters out extreme records that fall outside the normal interquartile range.

Implementation Steps:

  • For each numeric column, compute Q1 and Q3.
  • Remove any rows with values below Q1 1.5IQR or above Q3 + 1.5IQR.
  • Additionally, remove rows with non-positive Quantity or UnitPrice values.

Pros: Ensures a cleaner dataset for unsupervised learning and removes potential data entry errors and rare noise cases that may form artificial clusters.
Cons: Reduces dataset size, which may impact model robustness if a significant portion of the data is filtered. May exclude valid edge-case behaviors or niche customer types.

Both datasets will be retained and analyzed in parallel to understand how outlier handling influences the clustering results, especially regarding segment definitions, silhouette scores, and business interpretability.

In[14]:
# Create copies
ordata_w = ordata.copy()  # Winsorized version
ordata_r = ordata.copy()  # IQR-based removal

# Select numeric columns (excluding ID-type fields)
ordata_numeric_columns = ordata.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.difference(['CustomerID'])

### 1. Winsorization (1% tails capped)
for col in ordata_numeric_columns:
    ordata_w[col] = winsorize(ordata_w[col], limits=[0.01, 0.01])

# Optional: remove impossible values (e.g., negative quantities/prices)
ordata_w = ordata_w[(ordata_w['Quantity'] > 0) & (ordata_w['UnitPrice'] > 0)]

### 2. IQR Method for Outlier Removal
def remove_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower) & (df[column] <= upper)]

# Apply IQR filter for each feature
for col in ordata_numeric_columns:
    ordata_r = remove_outliers_iqr(ordata_r, col)

# Optional: remove impossible values
ordata_r = ordata_r[(ordata_r['Quantity'] > 0) & (ordata_r['UnitPrice'] > 0)]

from scipy.stats.mstats import winsorize

# Create copies for each outlier treatment strategy
rfmdata_w = rfmdata.copy()  # Winsorized version
rfmdata_r = rfmdata.copy()  # IQR-based removal

# Select numeric columns (excluding customer identifier if present)
rfm_numeric_columns = rfmdata.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.difference(['CustomerID'])

# --- 1. Winsorization (Capping at 1% tails) ---
for col in rfm_numeric_columns:
    rfmdata_w[col] = winsorize(rfmdata_w[col], limits=[0.01, 0.01])

# --- 2. IQR Method for Outlier Removal ---
def remove_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower) & (df[column] <= upper)]

# Apply IQR filter for each RFM feature
for col in rfm_numeric_columns:
    rfmdata_r = remove_outliers_iqr(rfmdata_r, col)

# Wrap labels
def wrap_labels(ax, df, col='Description', width=20):
    labels = []
    for i in ax.get_xticks():
        text = df[col].iloc[i]
        wrapped = '\n'.join([text[j:j+width] for j in range(0, len(text), width)])
        labels.append(wrapped)
    ax.set_xticks(range(len(df)))
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=6)

wrap_labels(ax, top_products)

# Add values on top

In[31]:
def create_rfm(df):
    """
    Generate RFM features from raw or preprocessed transactional data.

    Parameters:
        df (pd.DataFrame): Transactional data with columns ['CustomerID', 'InvoiceDate', 'Quantity', 'UnitPrice', 'InvoiceNo']

    Returns:
        pd.DataFrame: RFM table with columns ['CustomerID', 'Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary']
    """
    import pandas as pd
    import numpy as np

    # 1. Copy and clean the data
    data = df.copy()
    data = data.dropna(subset=["CustomerID"])
    data = data[(data["Quantity"] > 0) & (data["UnitPrice"] > 0)]
    data["InvoiceDate"] = pd.to_datetime(data["InvoiceDate"])

    # 2. Reference date (day after last invoice)
    reference_date = data["InvoiceDate"].max() + pd.Timedelta(days=1)

    # 3. RFM computation
    rfm = data.groupby("CustomerID").agg({
        "InvoiceDate": lambda x: (reference_date - x.max()).days,       # Recency
        "InvoiceNo": "nunique",                                         # Frequency
        "Quantity": lambda x: np.sum(x * data.loc[x.index, "UnitPrice"])  # Monetary
    }).reset_index()

    rfm.columns = ["CustomerID", "Recency", "Frequency", "Monetary"]
    return rfm

# IQR Removal
def remove_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower) & (df[column] <= upper)]

for col in numeric_cols:
    ordata_r = remove_outliers_iqr(ordata_r, col)
ordata_r = ordata_r[(ordata_r['Quantity'] > 0) & (ordata_r['UnitPrice'] > 0)]

def scale_rfm(df):
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    rfm_features = ['Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary']
    scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df[rfm_features])
    scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled, columns=rfm_features)
    scaled_df['CustomerID'] = df['CustomerID'].values
    return scaled_df[['CustomerID'] + rfm_features]

4.2. Number of Clusters initial Inference

Before applying clustering algorithms, it is essential to estimate the optimal number of clusters (k). This section uses two widely accepted methods: the Elbow Method and the Silhouette Score. These techniques guide us in selecting a k that balances model performance and interpretability.

4.2.1. Clusters Inference with Elbow Method

The Elbow Method is a widely used technique for identifying the optimal number of clusters (k) in unsupervised learning, particularly in K-Means clustering. The core idea is to evaluate how the total Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WSS) changes as the number of clusters increases.

*What is WSS?*

The Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WSS) measures the compactness of the clusters, i.e., how close the data points in a cluster are to the cluster centroid. It is computed as the sum of the squared Euclidean distances between each point and the centroid of its cluster.

*WSS Formula*

$WSS = \sum_{i=1}^{k} \sum_{x_j \in C_i} ||x_j - \mu_i||^2$

Where:

  • $(k)$ is the number of clusters
  • $C_i$ is the set of points in cluster ( i )
  • $\mu_i$ is the centroid of cluster ( i )
  • $x_j$ is an observation in cluster ( i )
  • $||x_j - \mu_i||^2$ is the squared distance between a point and its cluster centroid

*How the Elbow Method Works*

  1. Run K-Means clustering on the dataset for a range of ( k ) values (e.g., 1 to 10).
  2. For each ( k ), compute the WSS.
  3. Plot ( k ) against WSS to observe the trend.
  4. The "elbow" point (where the WSS starts to decrease more slowly) suggests the optimal number of clusters. This is the point where adding more clusters yields diminishing returns.

*Why It Works*

The elbow represents the point at which increasing the number of clusters beyond it results in only marginal gains in cluster compactness. Selecting ( k ) at the elbow helps avoid overfitting while capturing the main structure in the data.

4.2.2. Clusters Inference with Silhouette Method

The Silhouette Method evaluates the quality of clustering by measuring how well each data point lies within its cluster compared to other clusters.

For each sample i:

  • Let $a(i)$ be the mean intra-cluster distance (average distance between i and all other points in the same cluster).
  • Let $b(i)$ be the mean nearest-cluster distance (lowest average distance between i and points in the nearest different cluster).
  • The silhouette score $s(i)$ is calculated as:

$s(i) = \frac{b(i) - a(i)}{\max(a(i), b(i))}$

  • Values range from -1 to +1:
    • +1: Perfect match to its cluster, far from others.
    • 0: On the decision boundary.
    • -1: Wrongly assigned to the current cluster.

The average silhouette score across all samples indicates clustering quality for a given number of clusters k.

Higher average silhouette score = better-defined clusters.

4.3. Final Cluster Analysis using KMeans

K-Means is a widely used unsupervised learning algorithm for segmenting data into k distinct clusters. It works by partitioning the dataset such that the within-cluster sum of squares (WSS) is minimized, effectively grouping similar points together based on Euclidean distance to cluster centroids.

The iterative procedure includes:

  1. Initialization: Select k initial centroids, typically using KMeans++ to optimize placement.
  2. Assignment: Each point is assigned to the nearest centroid.
  3. Update: Recalculate centroids as the mean of all assigned points.
  4. Repeat: Repeat the assignment and update steps until convergence is achieved (i.e., no change in cluster assignments).

The dataset rfmdata_bw_S is ideal for K-Means due to the following reasons:

  • It is a cleaned version of the original customer transaction dataset, with outliers capped using Winsorization, reducing noise.
  • It has been normalized using MinMaxScaler, which scales Recency, Frequency, and Monetary values into a uniform [0, 1] range. This is essential because K-Means relies on Euclidean distance, which is sensitive to scale.
  • The RFM features provide a compact, yet powerful representation of customer behavior that benefits from centroid-based clustering.

It also gives the best Cluster separation quality through the silhouette analysis. We consider k = 3 and k = 4 as candidate cluster counts because:

  • These values were recommended by both the Elbow Method and the Silhouette Analysis in earlier steps.
  • k = 3 often yields an interpretable segmentation such as:
    • High-value customers
    • New or one-time buyers
    • At-risk or churned users
  • k = 4 may provide additional granularity, e.g., splitting high-frequency but low-monetary users into a new group.

These values provide a balance between model simplicity and business interpretability, without risking overfitting through excessive segmentation.

The following code applies KMeans to the dataset and create 2 new datasets rfmdata_bw_S_3C and rfmdata_bw_S_4C with the final Cluster assignments for each customer (in the new column Cluster)

5. Final Results and Conclusions

RFM Clustering Results (K=3)

After applying K-Means clustering with K=3 on normalized RFM values, we merged the cluster labels back into the original RFM dataset to interpret the clusters using real (non-normalized) values.

Cluster Interpretations:

Cluster 0 Best Customers

  • Avg Recency: 32 days
  • Avg Frequency: 5.47 purchases
  • Avg Monetary Value: $2,714
  • Customer Count: 2,906
  • Interpretation: These are highly engaged and high-spending customers who purchased recently. They represent the most loyal and profitable segment.
  • Strategy: Prioritize with exclusive offers, early access to promotions, and loyalty rewards.

Cluster 1 Churned Low Spenders

  • Avg Recency: 294 days
  • Avg Frequency: 1.35 purchases
  • Avg Monetary Value: $607
  • Customer Count: 626
  • Interpretation: These are inactive, one-time or low-frequency buyers with small transaction amounts.
  • Strategy: Use win-back campaigns, discounts, or reminders to re-engage this group.

Cluster 2 At-Risk Moderate Spenders

  • Avg Recency: 153 days
  • Avg Frequency: 2.22 purchases
  • Avg Monetary Value: $797
  • Customer Count: 806
  • Interpretation: These customers are moderate in value and purchased in the past, but haven't done so recently. They show signs of churn risk.
  • Strategy: Reconnect with targeted product recommendations and time-limited incentives.
